b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p8_nomenclature_binary" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title> Nomenclature for Binary Ionic Compounds </title>\n        <objref idref="chemical_formulas"/>\n        <objref idref="name_compounds"/>\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n\n        <p>In every ionic compound, the total number of positive charges of the cations equals the\n            total number of negative charges of the anions. Thus, ionic compounds are electrically\n            neutral overall, even though they contain positive and negative ions. We can use this\n            observation to help us write the formula of an ionic compound. The formula of an ionic\n            compound must have a ratio of ions such that the numbers of positive and negative\n            charges are equal.</p>\n        <p>A <extra><anchor>binary ionic compound</anchor><meaning><material><p>Ionic compound consisting of a monatomic cation and a monatomic anion.</p></material></meaning></extra> consists of a monatomic (formed from one atom) cation and a\n            monatomic anion. Note that the ending of the names of monatomic anions are changed to\n            -ide. For example, sulfide is an ion of sulfur and phosphide is an ion of\n            phosphorus.</p>\n        <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\n      \n        <dl>\n            <dt><em>Writing a Chemical Formula for Binary Ionic Compounds</em></dt>\n            <dd> <ol><li>Identify the cation and anion and their charges.</li>\n                <li>Combine the ions in the smallest whole number ratio such that the total\n                    number of positive charges is equal to the total number of negative\n                    charges.</li>\n                <li>Write the chemical formula that reflects this ratio.</li></ol></dd>\n        </dl>\n        <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\n        \n      \n        <example>\n            <p>Write the chemical formula for potassium sulfide.</p>\n            <ul>\n                <li>Determine the ionic charges.<p>Referring to the periodic table, we see that\n                        potassium will form a 1+ ion and sulfur will form a 2- ion, as illustrated\n                        in the diagrams below.</p>\n                    <image src="../webcontent/K_S_ion1.png"\n                        alt="1 potassium ion represented by a rectangle with 1 positive sign. 1 sulfide ion represented by a rectangle with 2 negative signs."\n                    /></li>\n                <li> Combine in a ratio that results in a neutral compound. <p>In order to obtain a\n                        neutral compound 2 potassium ions must combine with 1 sulfur ion. </p>\n                    <image src="../webcontent/K_S_ion2.png"\n                        alt="2 potassium ions combined with 1 sulfide ion."/></li>\n                <li>Resulting in a chemical formula of: K<sub>2</sub>S</li>\n            </ul>\n        </example>\n        <section>\n            <title>Criss-Cross Method of Writing Chemical Formulas</title>\n            <body>\n                <p>A convenient method to write chemical formulas is by using the criss-cross\n                    method. In this method the value of the ionic charge for the cation becomes the\n                    subscript of the anion in the chemical formula and the value of the ionic charge\n                    of the anion becomes the subscript of the cation in the chemical formula.\n                    Looking at the previous example we can see how the criss-cross method works.</p>\n                <image src="../webcontent/K_S_cross.png"\n                    alt="Symbol for a potassium ion with a K and +1 to the upper right and symbol for a sulfide ion with an S and a -2 to the upper right. There is an arrow from the +1 in the upper right of the K to the lower right of the S. There is an arrow from the -2 in the upper right of S to the lower right of K."/>\n                <p>Like the previous method, the result is K<sub>2</sub>S. One thing to remember with the\n                    criss-cross method is that the ratio of ions in a chemical formula of an ionic\n                    compound must always be in the smallest whole number ratio.</p>\n            </body>\n        </section>\n        <example>\n            <p>Write the chemical formula for magnesium oxide.</p>\n            <ul>\n                <li>Determine the ionic charges. </li>\n            </ul>\n            <image src="../webcontent/mgO_ions.png" alt="Symbol for magnesium ion with a 2+ charge and symbol for an oxide ion with a 2- charge."></image>\n            <ul>\n                <li> Use the criss-cross method. \n                    <image src="../webcontent/mgO_crisscross.png" alt="Symbol for a magnesium ion with a Mg and a 2+ to the upper right and symbol for a oxide ion with an O and a 2- to the upper right. There is an arrow from the 2+ in the upper right of the Mg to the lower right of the O. There is an arrow from the 2- in the upper right of O to the lower right of Mg."></image>\n                    <p>Notice the result of the criss-cross method results in:</p>\n                           <formula>Mg<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub></formula>\n                    <p>This 2:2 ratio of ions is reduced to 1:1, resulting in the formula:</p><formula> <em>MgO</em></formula>\n                </li>\n            </ul>\n        </example>\n          <wb:inline idref="compound_formula_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline> \n        <section>\n            <title><em>Naming Binary Ionic Compounds</em></title>\n            <body>\n                <p>Given the name of a binary ionic compound you can derive the formula and given\n                    the formula you can name the compound. </p>\n           \n                <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\n                <dl>\n                <dt>Naming Binary Ionic Compounds</dt>\n                <dd><ol>\n                    <li>Name the cation first. If the cation is monatomic, the name is the\n                        same as the element name.</li>\n                    <li>Name the anion second. If the anion is monatomic, change the ending\n                        of the element name to -ide.</li>\n                    <li>Add roman numeral that indicates the charge of the ion for cations\n                        that can have multiple charges.</li>\n                </ol></dd>\n            </dl>\n                <image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\n                \n               \n                <example>\n                    <p>Name the compound Li<sub>3</sub>P.</p>\n                    <ul>\n                        <li>Name the cation. <formula>The cation is lithium.</formula></li>\n                        <li>Name the anion, change its ending to -ide. <formula>The anion is the\n                                phosphorus ion, which we change the name to phosphide. </formula></li>\n                        <li>The name of the compound is: <p><formula><em>lithium phosphide</em></formula></p></li>\n                    </ul>\n                </example>\n                  <wb:inline idref="compound_name_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline> \n            </body>\n        </section>\n        <section>\n            <title>Naming Ionic Compounds with Multiple Charge Cations</title>\n            <body>\n                <p>In all of the examples we have looked at so far the cation in the formula can only\n                    form one ion. For example, when the calcium atom forms an ion, it is always\n                        Ca<sup>2+</sup> or when potassium forms an ion it is always K<sup>+</sup>.\n                    However some of the transition metals can form different ions. For example lead\n                    can form ion Pb<sup>2+</sup> and Pb<sup>4+</sup>. So when it combines with\n                    chlorine the result may be PbCl<sub>2</sub> or PbCl<sub>4</sub>. When we write\n                    the name for each of these formulas we need to indicate whether the compound is\n                    formed from the Pb<sup>2+</sup> and Pb<sup>4+</sup> ion. We do this using roman\n                    numerals. Where the roman numeral indicates the charge of the ion in the\n                    formula.</p>\n                <table>\n                    <tr>\n                        <td align="center"><em style="bold">Formula</em></td>\n                        <td align="center"><em style="bold">Cation in the Compound</em></td>\n                        <td align="center"><em style="bold">Name of the Compound</em></td>\n\n                    </tr>\n                    <tr>\n                        <td>PbCl<sub>2</sub></td>\n                        <td>Pb<sup>2+</sup></td>\n                        <td>lead(II) chloride</td>\n                    </tr>\n                    <tr>\n                        <td>PbCl<sub>4</sub></td>\n                        <td>Pb<sup>4+</sup></td>\n                        <td>lead(IV) chloride</td>\n                    </tr>\n                </table>\n                <p>Note that not all transition metals can form multiple cations. Here is a list of\n                    the most common.</p>\n                <table>\n                    <tr>\n                        <td align="center"><em style="bold">Formula</em></td>\n                        <td align="center"><em style="bold">Cation in the Compound</em></td>\n\n                    </tr>\n                    <tr>\n                        <td>Chromium(II)<p>Chromium(III)</p></td>\n                        <td>Cr<sup>2+</sup><p>Cr<sup>3+</sup></p></td>\n                    </tr>\n                    <tr>\n                        <td>Manganese(II)<p>Manganese(III)</p></td>\n                        <td>Mn<sup>2+</sup><p>Mn<sup>3+</sup></p></td>\n                    </tr>\n                    <tr>\n                        <td>Iron(II)<p>Iron(III)</p></td>\n                        <td>Fe<sup>2+</sup><p>Fe<sup>3+</sup></p></td>\n                    </tr>\n                    <tr>\n                        <td>Cobalt(II)<p>Cobalt(III)</p></td>\n                        <td>Co<sup>2+</sup><p>Co<sup>3+</sup></p></td>\n                    </tr>\n                    <tr>\n                        <td>Copper(I)<p>Copper(II)</p></td>\n                        <td>Cu<sup>+</sup><p>Cu<sup>2+</sup></p></td>\n                    </tr>\n                    <tr>\n                        <td>Mercury(I)<p>Mercury(II)</p></td>\n                        <td>Hg<sub>2</sub><sup>2+</sup><p>Hg<sup>2+</sup></p></td>\n                    </tr>\n                    <tr>\n                        <td>Tin(II)<p>Tin(IV)</p></td>\n                        <td>Sn<sup>2+</sup><p>Sn<sup>4+</sup></p></td>\n                    </tr>\n                    <tr>\n                        <td>Lead(II)<p>Lead(IV)</p></td>\n                        <td>Pb<sup>2+</sup><p>Pb<sup>4+</sup></p></td>\n                    </tr>\n\n                </table>\n                <p>It is also worth noting that the following metals always form the same ion.\n                    Silver always forms Ag<sup>+</sup>. Cadmium always forms Cd<sup>2+</sup>. Zinc always forms Zn<sup>2+</sup>.\n                    Gallium always forms Ga<sup>3+</sup>. Aluminum always forms Al<sup>3+</sup>.</p>\n                  <wb:inline idref="ion_name_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline>\n            </body>\n        </section>\n\n        <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n            >Openstax Chemistry</link> under <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n            href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n            >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'